# Emily LLM & Prompt Rules

## The Cardinal Rule
ALL prompt strings are defined and assembled in `llm/prompt_builder.py` — the ONLY place prompts live. Hardcoded prompt strings in any other module are a bug and must be moved to prompt_builder.

## Prompt Versioning
- Every named prompt has a version tag (e.g., `_EMILY_SYSTEM_PROMPT_V1`)
- When the self-improvement engine rewrites a prompt, the old version MUST be archived to `prompts/archive/<name>_<version>.txt` before the new version replaces it
- Never silently overwrite a prompt — the archive is the audit trail

## Prompt Assembly
- Use `PromptBuilder` methods to compose prompts from modular sections
- System prompt + persona + context + tools + user message = final prompt
- Prompts must be assembled, not concatenated with f-strings across files
- Include token budget awareness — trim context to fit the model's window

## Model Fleet
- Models are accessed through `llm/fleet.py` (LLMFleet) — never instantiate clients directly
- Model tiers: nano (routing), fast (conversation), smart (reasoning), vision (multimodal), embedding
- The router (`llm/router.py`) selects model tier based on complexity score — respect its decisions
- Streaming responses go through `llm/streaming.py`

## ReAct Loop
- Non-trivial tasks use the ReAct++ loop: THOUGHT → PLAN → ACTION → OBSERVATION → CRITIQUE → REVISE → RESPOND
- Implemented in `llm/react_loop.py` — tool calls are part of the loop, not separate
- CriticAgent scores outputs — below 0.65 triggers silent retry

## Structured Output
- Use `llm/structured_output.py` for JSON-schema-constrained generation
- Pydantic models define the expected output shape — never parse free-form text when structured output is available
